<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This species is found in the epipelagic zone (0-200 m depth) of Pacific and Indian Oceans (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
), the west coast of Florida (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" author="Pierce, EL" journalOrPublisher="The Biological Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="206 - 228" refId="B67" refString="Pierce, EL, 1951. The Chaetognatha of the west coast of Florida. The Biological Bulletin 100 (3): 206 - 228, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" title="The Chaetognatha of the west coast of Florida." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/1538532" volume="100" year="1951">Pierce 1951</bibRefCitation>
), Indian coast (
<bibRefCitation author="George, PC" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="657 - 689" refId="B28" refString="George, PC, 1952. A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast. Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India 18 (6): 657 - 689" title="A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast." volume="18" year="1952">George 1952</bibRefCitation>
) and the Tosa Bay in Japan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, specimens were found in the epipelagic zone (0-75 m depth) of the Yellow Sea (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
: station YS03). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Doncaster" baseAuthorityYear="1902" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Ferosagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ferosagitta robusta" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ferosagitta robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a typical Indo-pacific warm-water species (
<bibRefCitation author="George, PC" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="657 - 689" refId="B28" refString="George, PC, 1952. A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast. Proceedings of the National Institute of Sciences of India 18 (6): 657 - 689" title="A systematic account of the chaetognatha of the Indian coastal waters, with observations on their seasonal fluctuations along the Malabar Coast." volume="18" year="1952">George 1952</bibRefCitation>
). The horizontal distribution range is wider than the vertical range and many individuals are mainly found in the surface layer (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, this species rarely appeared under low temperature conditions and their presence was predominant in the sea area affected by warm currents. The temperature range in the sampling stations was within 25.87-28.70 °C and salinity range was 32.72-33.11 psu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
Characteristics of the species in Korean waters, such as the conspicuous intestinal diverticula, head and body width and the seminal vesicles shape, are consistent with previous records (
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chihara, M" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Indiana Academy of Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B15" refString="Chihara, M, Murano, M, 1997. An Illustrated Guide to Marine Plankton in Japan. Tokai University Press, 1571 pp." title="An Illustrated Guide to Marine Plankton in Japan. Tokai University Press, 1571 pp." year="1997">Chihara and Murano 1997</bibRefCitation>
). The main difference between this species and another congeneric species of Korea, 
<taxonomicName genus="F." lsidName="F. ferox" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="ferox">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">F. ferox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is the shape of the seminal vesicles. Seminal vesicles of 
<taxonomicName genus="F." lsidName="F. robusta" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">F. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very conspicuous, touching both posterior end of posterior fins, while that in 
<taxonomicName genus="F." lsidName="F. ferox" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="ferox">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">F. ferox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not so conspicuous and are close to both posterior fins and caudal fin (
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="186 - 201" refId="B3" refString="Alvarino, A, 1962. Taxonomic revision of Sagitta robusta and Sagitta ferox Doncaster, and notes on their distribution in the Pacific. Pacific Science 16: 186 - 201" title="Taxonomic revision of Sagitta robusta and Sagitta ferox Doncaster, and notes on their distribution in the Pacific." volume="16" year="1962">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
1962
</bibRefCitation>
). We observed one specimen for CBE staining pattern: dorsomedian line, 49 dots; dorsolateral line, 38 dots; lateral line, 30 dots; receptors on the lateral fin, 6 dots; anterolateral receptors on the caudal fin, 4 dots; posterior receptors on the caudal fin not observed due to damage.
</paragraph>
